  "text": "## Grafana Datasource Plugin Query Flow\n\nThe query flow from HTTP API handler to data frame response follows this chain:\n\n### 1. HTTP API Handler Entry Point\n**File**: `pkg/api/ds_query.go`\n**Function**: `QueryMetricsV2()` (lines 68-88)\n\nThis is the HTTP endpoint handler for `/api/ds/query`. It:\n- Receives the HTTP request and binds it to a `dtos.MetricRequest`\n- Calls `hs.queryDataService.QueryData()` or `hs.queryDataService.QueryDataNew()`\n- Returns the response via `hs.toJsonStreamingResponse()` which serializes to JSON\n\n### 2. Query Data Service\n**File**: `pkg/services/query/query.go`\n**Functions**: `queryData()`, `handleQuerySingleDatasource()` (lines 101-331)\n\nThe `queryData()` method:\n- Parses the metric request into queries grouped by datasource\n- Routes to appropriate handler: expressions, single datasource, or concurrent queries\n- For single datasource queries, calls `handleQuerySingleDatasource()` which:\n  - Gets the datasource and validates access\n  - Checks if query-service is available via `qsDatasourceClientBuilder.BuildClient()`\n  - For single-tenant flow: calls `s.pluginClient.QueryData()` directly at line 322\n  - For multi-tenant flow: converts to k8s request and calls query-service client\n\n### 3. Plugin Client Query Execution\n**File**: `pkg/plugins/plugins.go`\n**Function**: `QueryData()` (lines 329-335)\n\nThe Plugin struct's `QueryData()` method:\n- Gets the plugin client via `p.Client()`\n- Delegates to the actual backend plugin client (usually gRPC-based)\n\n### 4. Backend Plugin gRPC Client\n**File**: `pkg/plugins/backendplugin/grpcplugin/client_v2.go`\n**Function**: `QueryData()` (lines 162-166)\n\nThe ClientV2's `QueryData()` method:\n- Checks if `DataClient` is available\n- Calls the gRPC service to execute the query on the backend plugin\n- Returns `*backend.QueryDataResponse` containing the query results and data frames\n\n### 5. Alternative: Aggregator Plugin Handler\n**File**: `pkg/aggregator/apiserver/plugin/query.go`\n**Function**: `QueryDataHandler()` (lines 20-89)\n\nFor aggregator-based plugins:\n- Receives HTTP request containing `data.QueryDataRequest`\n- Decodes JSON into `data.QueryDataRequest` (line 26)\n- Converts to backend.QueryDataRequest format (line 75)\n- Calls `h.client.QueryData()` (the plugin client)\n- Wraps response in `aggregationv0alpha1.QueryDataResponse`\n\n### 6. HTTP Response Serialization\n**File**: `pkg/aggregator/apiserver/util/responder.go`\n**Function**: `Object()` (lines 16-18)\n\nThe `Responder.Object()` method:\n- Takes the status code and response object\n- Calls `responsewriters.WriteRawJSON()` from Kubernetes API server library\n- This uses the runtime.Object encoding to serialize the response to JSON\n\n### 7. Response Data Structure\n**File**: `pkg/aggregator/apis/aggregation/v0alpha1/types.go`\n**Struct**: `QueryDataResponse` (lines 130-136)\n\nThe `QueryDataResponse` struct:\n- Embeds Kubernetes TypeMeta (for API versioning)\n- Wraps `backend.QueryDataResponse` from grafana-plugin-sdk-go\n- The `backend.QueryDataResponse` contains a map of `RefID -> DataResponse`\n- Each `DataResponse` contains:\n  - `Frames: []*data.Frame` - Array of data frames containing the query results\n  - `Error` - Optional error message\n  - Status information\n\n### Data Frame Serialization\nData frames are serialized as part of the `backend.QueryDataResponse` JSON encoding. The frames contain:\n- Field definitions (name, type, labels)\n- Field values (time series data, logs, etc.)\n- Frame metadata (type, ref ID, etc.)\n\nThis complete flow ensures that:\n1. Frontend queries reach the HTTP API\n2. Queries are routed to appropriate datasource plugins\n3. Backend plugins execute and return results as data frames\n4. Results are serialized to JSON and returned to the frontend\n"

